0.title: adjective
0.description: Adjectives are words that typically modify nouns and specify their properties or attributes.

1.title: adposition
1.description: Adposition is a cover term for prepositions and postpositions. Adpositions belong to a closed set of items that occur before (preposition) or after (postposition) a complement composed of a noun phrase, noun, pronoun, or clause that functions as a noun phrase, and that form a single structure with the complement to express its grammatical and semantic relation to another unit within a clause.

2.title: adverb
2.description: Adverbs are words that typically modify verbs for such categories as time, place, direction or manner. They may also modify adjectives and other adverbs.

3.title: auxiliary
3.description: An auxiliary is a function word that accompanies the lexical verb of a verb phrase and expresses grammatical distinctions not carried by the lexical verb, such as person, number, tense, mood, aspect, voice or evidentiality.

4.title: coordinating conjunction
4.description: A coordinating conjunction is a word that links words or larger constituents without syntactically subordinating one to the other and expresses a semantic relationship between them.

5.title: determiner
5.description: Determiners are words that modify nouns or noun phrases and express the reference of the noun phrase in context. That is, a determiner may indicate whether the noun is referring to a definite or indefinite element of a class, to a closer or more distant element, to an element belonging to a specified person or thing, to a particular number or quantity, etc. Includes pro-adjectives, indefinite articles, definite articles.

6.title: interjection
6.description: An interjection is a word that is used most often as an exclamation or part of an exclamation. It typically expresses an emotional reaction, is not syntactically related to other accompanying expressions, and may include a combination of sounds not otherwise found in the language.

7.title: noun
7.description: Nouns are a part of speech typically denoting a person, place, thing, animal or idea.

8.title: numeral
8.description: A numeral is a word, functioning most typically as a determiner, adjective or pronoun, that expresses a number and a relation to the number, such as quantity, sequence, frequency or fraction.

9.title: other
9.description: The tag X is used for words that for some reason cannot be assigned a real part-of-speech category. It should be used very restrictively.

10.title: particle
10.description: Particles are function words that must be associated with another word or phrase to impart meaning and that do not satisfy definitions of other universal parts of speech (e.g. adpositions, coordinating conjunctions, subordinating conjunctions or auxiliary verbs). Particles may encode grammatical categories such as negation, mood, tense etc. Particles are normally not inflected, although exceptions may occur.

11.title: pronoun
11.description: Pronouns are words that substitute for nouns or noun phrases, whose meaning is recoverable from the linguistic or extralinguistic context.

12.title: proper noun
12.description: A proper noun is a noun (or nominal content word) that is the name (or part of the name) of a specific individual, place, or object.

13.title: punctuation
13.description: Punctuation marks are non-alphabetical characters and character groups used in many languages to delimit linguistic units in printed text.

14.title: subordinating conjunction
14.description: A subordinating conjunction is a conjunction that links constructions by making one of them a constituent of the other. The subordinating conjunction typically marks the incorporated constituent which has the status of a (subordinate) clause.

15.title: symbol
15.description: A symbol is a word-like entity that differs from ordinary words by form, function, or both.

16.title: verb
16.description: A verb is a member of the syntactic class of words that typically signal events and actions, can constitute a minimal predicate in a clause, and govern the number and types of other constituents which may occur in the clause.

0.title: a foreign word
0.description: Is this a foreign word? Not a loan word and not a foreign name but a genuinely foreign word appearing inside native text, e.g. inside direct speech, titles of books etc.

1.title: abbreviation
1.description: Is this an abbreviation? Note that the abbreviated word(s) typically belongs to a part of speech other than X.

2.title: animacy
2.description: Similarly to Gender (and to the African noun classes), animacy is usually a lexical feature of nouns and inflectional feature of other parts of speech (pronouns, adjectives, determiners, numerals, verbs) that mark agreement with nouns.

3.title: Aspect
3.description: Aspect is a feature that specifies duration of the action in time, whether the action has been completed etc.

5.title: clusivity
5.description: Clusivity is a feature of first-person plural personal pronouns. As such, it can also be reflected by inflection of verbs.

6.title: definiteness or state
6.description: Definiteness is typically a feature of nouns, adjectives and articles. Its value distinguishes whether we are talking about something known and concrete, or something general or unknown.

7.title: degree of comparison
7.description: Degree of comparison is typically an inflectional feature of some adjectives and adverbs.

11.title: form of verb or deverbative
11.description: Some verb forms in some languages actually form a gray zone between verbs and other parts of speech (nouns, adjectives and adverbs).

13.title: misspelled word
13.description: Indicates bad spelling, grammatical error etc.

15.title: mood
15.description: Mood is a feature that expresses modality and subclassifies finite verb forms.

16.title: noun class
16.description: NounClass is similar to Gender and Animacy because it is to a large part a lexical category of nouns and other parts of speech inflect for it to show agreement (pronouns, adjectives, determiners, numerals, verbs).

18.title: numeral type
18.description: It includes almost everything where counting is involved and there are various subtypes and applies to seral part-of-speach tags(NUM, DET, ADJ, ADV).

8.title: Zero person
8.description: Zero person is for impersonal statements, appears in Finnish as well as in Santa Ana Pueblo Keres.

20.title: Polarity
20.description: Polarity is typically a feature of verbs, adjectives, sometimes also adverbs and nouns in languages that negate using bound morphemes.

21.title: politeness
21.description: Various languages have various means to express politeness or respect; some of the means are morphological. Three to four dimensions of politeness are distinguished in linguistic literature.

22.title: possessive
22.description: It tells whether the word is possessive.

23.title: pronominal type
23.description: This feature typically applies to pronouns, pronominal adjectives (determiners), pronominal numerals (quantifiers) and pronominal adverbs.

24.title: reflexive
24.description: It tells whether the word is reflexive, i.e. refers to the subject of its clause.

0.title: Active Voice
0.description: The subject of the verb is the doer of the action (agent), the object is affected by the action (patient). This label is also used for the actor-focus voice of Austronesian languages.

9.title: Middle Voice
9.description: Between active and passive, needed e.g. in Ancient Greek or Sanskrit. The subject is both doer and undergoer in a sense: he is acting upon himself.

0.title: declarative
0.description: declare a fact, an event, a state or a case for something.

2.title: Expressed Condition
2.description: Condition expressed by verb first order

4.title: Incomplete
4.description: A phrase which is cut off.

6.title: Proverb
6.description: Idioms, proverbs, slangs, expressions, and sayings

7.title: Reference
7.description: A pop culture reference or mention of something contemporary from consuming media such as books, movies, comics, etc.

7.title: Courtesy Greeting
7.description: Questions such as "how are you?", and "how is it going?".

9.title: Query Understanding
9.description: Question asking for whether established parameters in context are underestod.

14.title: Query Recommendation
14.description: Query one or more entities. filterable.

5.title: Morphology
5.description: Study of words and it's changes.

0.title: Contractions
0.description: shortened form of a word (or group of words) that omits certain letters or sounds

1.title: Stop Words
1.description: The words don't add meaning to phrase and are generally filtered out before some NLP processes.

0.title: Clause
0.description: Groups of words that contain both a subject and a predicate. a clause has all the components of a potentially independent sentence.

1.title: Bound morphemes
1.description: appear only as parts of words, always in conjunction with a root and sometimes with other bound morphemes.

2.title: Free Morpheme
2.description: can function independently as words and can appear within lexemes.

3.title: Phrase
3.description: A phrase is a group of two or more words functioning as a meaningful unit within a sentence or clause.

5.title: Term(Constituent)
5.description: One re more words conveying a meaning.

0.title: Axiom
0.description: Axiom are the properties of relations used for constrain values for classes or instances.

2.title: Event
2.description: the changing of attributes or relations.

3.title: Instance
3.description: A named instance(or object). can have a specific type.

1.title: Artifacts
1.description: Man made things, such as statues, devices, even websites and apps

2.title: Cardinal
2.description: Cardinal numbers which don't represent an instance type.

3.title: Date
3.description: Absolute or relative date or time

5.title: Event
5.description: Named hurricanes, battles, wars, sports events, etc.

7.title: Geographical Location
7.description: Geographic locations such as mountains, boddies of water.

9.title: Group(nationality, religion,...)
9.description: Group of people sharing nationality, religion, political party.

12.title: Natural Phenomenon
12.description: Storms, Disasters and other natural phenomenon

15.title: Percentage
15.description: Percentages including %, or formats such as 50/50.

19.title: Quantity
19.description: Measurments including it's unit. such as weight, lenght.

21.title: Work of art
21.description: Title of books, movies, music, etc.

5.description: Restrictions, rules and conditions which a relation may take on.

7.title: Phonology
7.description: The study of speech structure within a language, including both the patterns of basic speech units and the accepted rules of pronunciation, is known as phonology.

0.title: Properties
0.description: The class of properties used to describe speech sounds.
